export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>Three demonstrated data fixes, eleven discovery chains, ten dated external gates — the whole planning inventory of this chapter. Chapters 15–17 supplied the pieces (the conviction ranking, the two policy maps, the compute ladder of Table 19.1); here they become a sequence: what gets fixed, in what order, validated how, against which dates I cannot move. The binding rule (§18.4): every milestone names the measured error gap it closes, or it does not enter the plan. Unmarked MAE means mean absolute error.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 18.1 — The phased program: every error-correction milestone closes a named, measured gap (statuses as of 2026-07-17; chain IDs per Table 15.1; scoreboard rows per Table 3.2; compute rungs per Table 19.1).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Phase</th>\n<th>Error-correction milestone (gap it closes)</th>\n<th>Validation milestone</th>\n<th>Discovery target (chain ID)</th>\n<th>Funding/compute gate</th>\n<th>Hard external gate</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1: months 0–24</td>\n<td>Replicate Rows 1–3 plus curvature-targeted phonon fine-tuning (PFT) on my classes: non-equilibrium augmentation (5–17× out-of-distribution error cuts at identical architecture <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"19\">[19]</sup>); 1→100-frame dose-response <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"87\">[87]</sup>; 90:10 Δ-learning (one study <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup>); PFT (single study <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"88\">[88]</sup>)</td>\n<td>MS25-style observable-first benchmark public (0.74 eV barrier recovered only ±0.06 eV at ~0.2 meV/atom energy error <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup>); compliant Matbench Discovery submission (SOTA F1 0.931 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"97\">[97]</sup>); OpenKIM deposit, passing checks <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"115\">[115]</sup></td>\n<td>Chain 1 (barrier MAE 0.310–0.349 eV vs 60 meV floor <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup>); Chain 4 (MS25 five-element alloy at 4–5× threshold <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup>); Chain 10 loop stood up</td>\n<td>NSF SBIR pitch → 2026-11-04 window <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"27\">[27]</sup>; DOE SBIR summer 2026 (agency-signaled <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"423\">[423]</sup>); ACCESS + EuroHPC free tiers <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"441\">[441]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"442\">[442]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"443\">[443]</sup>; ERCAP SBIR pool <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup>; NAIRR on first award <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"426\">[426]</sup>; Genesis Phase II as lab sub <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"25\">[25]</sup></td>\n<td>2026-07-27 first NSF deadline (pitch mechanics <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"27\">[27]</sup>); ERCAP closes early Oct 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>; 2026-11-10 rare-earth rule lapse <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2: years 2–5</td>\n<td>Chain campaigns: barrier-targeted training toward ≤40 meV MAE; spin-aware multi-fidelity stack (<span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> errors 15–35%, sign-unstable <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"13\">[13]</sup>; coercivity ~5× <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup>); disorder-native/MoE potentials toward ≤2.5 meV/atom <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup>; Δ-learned adsorption toward ~0.1 eV vs the 0.2–0.4 eV GGA floor <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"12\">[12]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"73\">[73]</sup></td>\n<td>Prospective barriers against fresh DFT nudged-elastic-band (NEB) paths; coercivity bounds against experiment; Director's Discretionary scaling plots toward INCITE readiness <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup>; first industrial JDA/framework agreement (Kemira shape <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"240\">[240]</sup>)</td>\n<td>Chains 1, 2, 3, 4 primary; 5–6 secondary; 10 running</td>\n<td>ALCC ~Nov 2026 — funded applicants only <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>; Director's Discretionary benchmarking <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup>; MAGNITO-class topicals <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"57\">[57]</sup>; Genesis follow-ons <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"25\">[25]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"183\">[183]</sup></td>\n<td>end-2027 BEST completion <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"59\">[59]</sup>; 2027 SPARC first plasma <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"446\">[446]</sup>; 2028 Helion PPA <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"294\">[294]</sup>; 15FYP window closes 2030 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3: years 5–10</td>\n<td>Rare-event hand-off: cascade→rate theory with calibrated UQ source terms (240 ps vs 5-yr service <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"15\">[15]</sup>); anharmonic MLIP collapsing the 93%-DFPT block <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"129\">[129]</sup>; correlation-capability build (Chain 9)</td>\n<td>Licensing-citable qualification package before DONES data; INCITE only at demonstrated ≥20%-of-machine readiness <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"447\">[447]</sup>; majority-survival autonomous-lab record <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"149\">[149]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"448\">[448]</sup></td>\n<td>Chains 7, 8, 10; 9 and 11 as frontier options</td>\n<td>INCITE (up to 60% of Frontier/Aurora <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"70\">[70]</sup>); milestone/FIRE-class fusion R&amp;D (&gt;<span class=\"math\">$350M private; ~$</span>220M FIRE <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"298\">[298]</sup>)</td>\n<td>~2034 IFMIF-DONES first fusion-spectrum data <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup>; 2039 ITER DT operations <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"291\">[291]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Read vertically, the table argues sequencing, not ambition. Phase 1 spends the stack's cheapest fixes — GPU-days to GPU-weeks of dataset work — to buy the only currency later phases accept: public, third-party-checkable validation. The chain column narrows deliberately to two-plus-one: chains 1 and 4 carry H/M-rated fixes with public acceptance tests; chain 10 runs underneath because its stability loop de-risks every deliverable. Phase 2 converts validation into campaigns and a first commercial structure; Phase 3 spends accumulated scaling evidence on the one simulation-or-nothing problem. The last column is the discipline: compute windows are deadlines; the geopolitical dates are weather.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s18-1-1", "html": "<p>Phase one replicates what named groups have demonstrated, on my target classes, before I claim anything new — Chapter 3's replication sequence executed verbatim. Four fixes, in order: single-structure-to-~100-frame dose-response fine-tuning on one solid-electrolyte and one high-entropy-alloy family, the cheapest fix in the stack <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"87\">[87]</sup>; non-equilibrium augmentation at 10⁴–10⁵ rattled and strained structures, the largest verified data lever <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"19\">[19]</sup>; 90:10 GGA:SCAN Δ-learning on adsorption and formation-energy labels — one study's 8×-data equivalence, treated as a hypothesis to reproduce, not a result <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup>; and PFT, a single study's 55% phonon-property error cut <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"88\">[88]</sup>. Validation comes first: an observable-first benchmark in the MS25 discipline (a 0.74 eV barrier can sit ±0.06 eV off at ~0.2 meV/atom energy error <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup>), a compliant Matbench Discovery submission <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"97\">[97]</sup>, and an OpenKIM deposit with passing Verification Checks <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"115\">[115]</sup> — all public before any request above Table 19.1's free rungs.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s18-1-2", "html": "<p>The gates sort by friction. Immediately live as of 2026-07-17: NSF ACCESS and EuroHPC's free SME tiers, the latter via an EU or Horizon-associated collaboration <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"441\">[441]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"442\">[442]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"443\">[443]</sup>; the NSF SBIR pitch track, where the 2026-07-27 deadline is unreachable by design — pitch review takes weeks, only invited pitches admit full proposals — so my window is 2026-11-04 and the pitch goes in beforehand to keep it open <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"27\">[27]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"27\">[27]</sup>; and a NAIRR request the day any award lands <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"426\">[426]</sup>. Later summer adds the DOE SBIR solicitation (agency-signaled, not yet published <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"423\">[423]</sup>) and, around August, the ERCAP AY2027 window with its SBIR pool <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup>, closing in early October <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>. Genesis Phase II selections are pending; my entry is as funded sub to a national-lab prime <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"25\">[25]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"183\">[183]</sup>. Chain Reaction Innovations reopens September 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"430\">[430]</sup>.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s18-2-1", "html": "<p>Phase two spends Phase one's credibility on the conviction ranking's top band (§15.3). Chain 1 runs the barrier campaign against fresh DFT-NEB paths, driving the 0.310–0.349 eV MAE measured across 574 paths <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup> toward the ≤40 meV threshold (≈1 kcal/mol). Chain 2 runs the magnet campaign on a dated clock: a spin-aware, multi-fidelity stack attacking sign-unstable 15–35% Curie-temperature errors <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"13\">[13]</sup> and the ~5× coercivity overestimate <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup>, inside MAGNITO's chemistry-and-microstructure mandate <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"57\">[57]</sup> and ahead of the 2026-11-10 rule lapse <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup>; solved means ranking-faithful magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy and <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>. Chain 4 pushes disorder-native potentials toward ≤2.5 meV/atom on a DFT-labeled, short-range-order-resolved benchmark — one benchmark suite's 617.9 → 3.5 meV/atom datum says this is within reach of demonstration <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup>. Chain 3 runs Δ-learned hybrid screening toward ~0.1 eV adsorption error against the 0.2–0.4 eV GGA floor <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"12\">[12]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"73\">[73]</sup>. Compute steps up one rung: ALCC at the expected ~November 2026 call, permissible only because federal funding will then exist <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>, with Director's Discretionary benchmarking accumulating INCITE's scaling evidence <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup>. The exit condition is one industrial JDA in the Kemira shape: a validated, narrowed candidate set with property data, delivered on a deadline <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"240\">[240]</sup>.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s18-3-1", "html": "<p>INCITE is a Phase-three instrument by evidence, not calendar: the first opening is the ~April 2027 call <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"70\">[70]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup>, but I submit only when Director's Discretionary data demonstrate the de-facto filter — effective use of ≥20% of the machine — and only inside a lab-led consortium <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"447\">[447]</sup>. The payload is Chain 7: a cascade-to-rate-theory hand-off whose every source term carries a calibrated, misspecification-aware error bar <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"93\">[93]</sup>, bridging the best cascade MLIP's 240 ps against a five-year service life <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"15\">[15]</sup> and the ~20 dpa validation wall (one industry synthesis's framing; the embrittlement data beneath are peer-reviewed <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"6\">[6]</sup>) against DEMO's 50-dpa second blanket <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"7\">[7]</sup>. The horizon is the facility clock: the package must be citable before IFMIF-DONES produces fusion-spectrum data around 2034 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup>, while BEST completes end-2027 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"59\">[59]</sup>, SPARC targets first plasma in 2027 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"446\">[446]</sup>, and Helion's Microsoft PPA falls due in 2028 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"294\">[294]</sup> — all designing around the bottleneck Chain 7 attacks, with a ~25 kg civilian tritium stockpile against 55.8 kg burned per gigawatt of fusion-thermal power per full-power year <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"311\">[311]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"312\">[312]</sup>. The same scale serves Chain 8: an anharmonic MLIP collapses the DFPT electron-phonon block consuming 93% of JARVIS hydride-workflow compute <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"129\">[129]</sup>. Chain 10 runs underneath: the stability-first loop with autonomous-lab partners — Polybot-class user facilities <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"448\">[448]</sup>, Genesis Area 11 infrastructure <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"149\">[149]</sup> — its majority-survival record published and independently reproduced before I call it solved.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s18-4", "html": "<p>Table 18.2 registers the ten dates the program is planned against; Figure 18.1 draws the three phases across them.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 18.2 — Time-gate register (all dates and statuses as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Date</th>\n<th>Event</th>\n<th>Consequence for this program</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>2026-07-27</td>\n<td>First NSF SBIR full-proposal deadline (solicitation 26-510) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"27\">[27]</sup></td>\n<td>Start gun, not my gate: mandatory pitch review <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"27\">[27]</sup> puts my entry at 2026-11-04; the pitch submitted beforehand keeps November open.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>~Aug 2026</td>\n<td>ERCAP AY2027 window opens; closes early Oct <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup></td>\n<td>First allocation I can hold: request through the SBIR pool (100,800 CPU + 58,800 GPU node-h, AY2025 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup>) the day an award exists; a miss costs twelve months.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>~Nov 2026</td>\n<td>ALCC 2027–28 call expected <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup></td>\n<td>Conditional: submit only with federal funding and a named DOE sponsor — ALCC awards time, never dollars, to the already-funded <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup>; otherwise skip a cycle.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2026-11-10</td>\n<td>October 2025 rare-earth export-rule suspension lapses <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup></td>\n<td>Chain 2's repricing event and my China compliance gate: nothing in the plan depends on renewal; a lapse accelerates the magnets campaign and freezes any PRC-presence decision.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>end-2027</td>\n<td>BEST device completion; blanket-module tests <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"59\">[59]</sup></td>\n<td>First burning-plasma tritium-breeding test bed; demand appears for the breeding-ceramic and RAFM validation data Chain 7 supplies.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2027</td>\n<td>SPARC first plasma targeted; Q&gt;1 goal <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"446\">[446]</sup></td>\n<td>Private fusion starts engineering around the materials bottleneck; validated first-wall and cascade simulation gains its first commercial buyers (milestone cohort: &gt;$350M private follow-on <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"298\">[298]</sup>).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2028</td>\n<td>Helion–Microsoft PPA power due, with penalties <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"294\">[294]</sup></td>\n<td>The first delivery obligation with financial teeth; licensing-grade uncertainty quantification becomes a procurement line item rather than a virtue.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>~2034</td>\n<td>IFMIF-DONES fully operational; first fusion-spectrum data <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup></td>\n<td>My qualification package must be citable before this date to shape what gets measured; afterward the 20-dpa wall starts falling and late entrants chase data.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2039</td>\n<td>ITER deuterium–tritium operations (Baseline 2024) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"291\">[291]</sup></td>\n<td>The conservative backstop: if simulation-led qualification has not demonstrated value by ITER's DT phase, the long game has failed on its own terms.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2026–2030</td>\n<td>15FYP window: fifteen named material classes funded whole-chain; codified on-ramps cluster 2026–27 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup></td>\n<td>The decision window for any China research presence; the dual-alignment posture of Chapter 16 holds — engagement designed so nothing depends on the 2026-11-10 suspension being renewed.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The register splits into two families demanding opposite postures. Rows 1–3 and 10 are calendar and eligibility gates — dates I can prepare for and must not miss; four of ten land inside 2026 H2, so Phase one's first hundred days carry three submissions (pitch, ERCAP, Chain Reaction) on top of the replication work. Rows 4–9 are weather: export-control law and tokamak construction schedules no proposal can move. The load-bearing asymmetry sits in rows 5–8: BEST, SPARC, and Helion all precede row 8's first fusion-spectrum data — private programs already pay to design around the bottleneck Chain 7 attacks — and row 8 precedes row 9 by five years, giving a qualification package a market before the conservative program needs one. Every date was set by someone else; none can be negotiated with, only met.</p>\n<figure class=\"fig\"><img src=\"/charts/roadmap-timeline.png\" alt=\"Figure 18.1 — The three phases against the nine dated hard external gates and the 2026–2030 15FYP window (shaded band). Phase bars are this chapter's program; gate markers are dates set externally, as of 2026-07-17.\" loading=\"lazy\"/><figcaption>Figure 18.1 — The three phases against the nine dated hard external gates and the 2026–2030 15FYP window (shaded band). Phase bars are this chapter's program; gate markers are dates set externally, as of 2026-07-17.</figcaption></figure>\n<p><em>Scope and sources: phase definitions from Table 18.1; gate dates from Table 18.2 citations (corpus dim07, dim11, dim12, dim13; as of 2026-07-17); &quot;~&quot; marks expected but not yet formally published calls.</em></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s18-4-1", "html": "<p>The anchoring rule binds every cell of Table 18.1: each error-correction milestone back-references the quantified gap it closes — a scoreboard row, a chain's current-versus-solved pair — and anything that cannot name its number does not enter the plan. &quot;Develop AI capabilities&quot; is not a milestone; &quot;held-out barrier MAE ≤ 150 meV on two electrolyte families by month 24&quot; is. The same rule generates the kill criteria, stated as first-person commitments. <strong>First, the fidelity wedge:</strong> if the 90:10 GGA:SCAN recipe — one study's result <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup> — fails to reproduce on the hardest class I attempt, the wedge narrows to pure dataset interventions, and chains 2–3 re-baseline their solved targets to PBE-class labels with declared uncertainty. <strong>Second, the barrier wedge:</strong> if, after non-equilibrium augmentation, micro-dose fine-tuning, and PFT on two solid-electrolyte families, held-out barrier MAE stays above 150 meV — more than half the road from 310–349 meV to 40 meV still unclosed — I stop selling barrier accuracy, publish the negative result as an MS25-style benchmark artifact, and Chain 1 survives as a dataset-plus-validation contribution. <strong>Third, the fusion long game:</strong> if by 2030 — four years before DONES data — no lab-led consortium or milestone-company team has adopted the cascade-to-rate-theory hand-off with calibrated source terms, or the uncertainty bounds fail to envelop ion-irradiation observables, I exit Chain 7's qualification ambition and keep only the tungsten/RAFM data-and-UQ services line into FIRE-class programs <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"298\">[298]</sup>. Dependencies run one direction — funding unlocks ERCAP and ALCC, validation unlocks JDAs and consortia, Chain 10 de-risks every deliverable — so the program fails in the order it is built. The nearest gate is ten days out; the pitch goes in before it, and the work starts with the cheapest demonstrated fix in the stack.</p>\n" },
]
